
A college student posted a sarcastic comment about a group project in the class WhatsApp group, saying, “Some people never do any work.” The message was unclear and did not mention anyone directly, but one student assumed it was about him. He felt offended and replied angrily. Soon, other classmates joined the conversation, and the situation turned into a heated argument. The misunderstanding affected teamwork, and the group struggled to complete the assignment on time. The teacher later noticed the conflict and had to intervene.

This problem could have been avoided if the student had communicated clearly and respectfully. Instead of posting publicly, they could have privately discussed concerns with the team members. Using polite language, avoiding sarcasm, and confirming facts before posting would have helped prevent misunderstanding. Responsible digital communication promotes collaboration and maintains a positive learning environment.
